nOutput: 13\nExplanation:\nWe remove some bricks to make heights = [5,3,3,1,1], the peak is at index 0.\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: heights = [6,5,3,9,2,7]\nOutput: 22\nExplanation:\nWe remove some bricks to make heights = [3,3,3,9,2,2], the peak is at index 3.\n\nExample 3:\n\nInput: heights = [3,2,5,5,2,3]\nOutput: 18\nExplanation:\nWe remove some bricks to make heights = [2,2,5,5,2,2], the peak is at index 2 or 3.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= n == heights.length <= 103\n1 <= heights[i] <= 109\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumSumOfHeights(self, heights: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def maximumSumOfHeights(self, heights: List[int]) -> int:\n        n = len(heights)\n        \n        # Initialize left and right arrays\n        left = [0] * n\n        right = [0] * n\n        \n        # Stack for left\n        stack = []\n        for i in range(n):\n            while stack and heights[stack[-1]] >= heights[i]:\n                stack.pop()\n            if stack:\n                left[i] = left[stack[-1]] + heights[i] * (i - stack[-1])\n            else:\n                left[i] = heights[i] * (i + 1)\n            stack.append(i)\n        \n        # Stack for right\n        stack = []\n        for i in range(n - 1, -1, -1):\n            while stack and heights[stack[-1]] >= heights[i]:\n                stack.pop()\n            if stack:\n                right[i] = right[stack[-1]] + heights[i] * (stack[-1] - i)\n            else:\n                right[i] = heights[i] * (n - i)\n            stack.append(i)\n        \n        # Calculate the maximum sum of heights for mountain shape\n        max_sum = 0\n        for i in range(n):\n            max_sum = max(max_sum, left[i] + right[i] - heights[i])\n        \n        return max_sum\n```\n\nThis solution uses two auxiliary arrays, `left` and `right`, to store the maximum possible sum of heights of non-decreasing sequences ending at each index from the left and non-increasing sequences starting at each index from the right, respectively. It then calculates the maximum possible sum of heights for a mountain shape by considering each index as the peak. The use of stacks helps efficiently calculate the sums in linear time.", "estimated_date": 1695513600000}